{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7c497aee-3440-4a23-8bd4-89a0eefc6e1c","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_011DAjVyvU2zUuwq7FfFA7w9","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Explaining C# 13 breaks"},"type":"function"}],"interactionId":"0072a92a-85d4-4edd-9476-7109fe48df9d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case:\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `InlineArray` on a `record struct`: C# 13 prohibits `InlineArray` on record structs. The fix is to use a plain `struct` instead of `record struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in iterator methods via local functions: C# 13 changed the rules. In C# 12, `stackalloc` was allowed in local functions within iterator methods. In C# 13, this is no longer allowed because the compiler now allows `unsafe` code in iterator methods directly, but `stackalloc` is specifically prohibited in iterators (and local functions within iterators are now considered part of the iterator). The fix is to extract the local function to a separate static method, or refactor to avoid stackalloc in the iterator context.\n\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the iterator change. In C# 12, local functions within iterators could use unsafe code and stackalloc because they were treated as separate from the iterator state machine. But in C# 13, the compiler relaxed restrictions on unsafe code in iterators themselves, which changed how local functions are handled—they're now more tightly integrated with the iterator, so stackalloc is no longer permitted in that context.\n\nThe solution is to extract the local function into a separate static method outside the iterator.\n\nFor the Resolver.cs issue, the problem is with overload resolution for collection expressions. In C# 12, `[]` would resolve to `ReadOnlySpan<int>` in certain scenarios, but C# 13 changed how collection expressions work with `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`—both are now valid targets, creating ambiguity when the empty collection is used. and in C# 13 with first-class span types, the new implicit conversions between array types and span types create ambiguity in overload resolution when both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>` are viable targets for an empty collection expression.\n\nThe solution is to explicitly specify which span type to use, either by calling a static method like `ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty` or by casting the collection expression directly.\n\nFor the actual issues: `Buffer.cs` has an `[InlineArray]` attribute on a `record struct`, which C# 13 no longer allows—I need to change it to a regular `struct`.  `Generator.cs` uses `stackalloc` inside a local function within an iterator method, which is now prohibited, so I'll extract that to a separate static method. And `Resolver.cs` has the overload resolution ambiguity with `Process([])` due to first-class span types, which I can fix with an explicit cast or by using a typed empty span constant.","outputTokens":1322,"requestId":"C426:2100D9:1C86B06:2007FAD:6A07BF7F"},"id":"61192b43-afcd-4d68-a20b-75344eebc0c8","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:39.451Z","parentId":"bbdad4bd-8d4b-4c77-b55a-bc36bd6790c1"}
