{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9418b51c-5ce5-4628-b606-4dfcf925d5c6","content":"Here's what breaks in each case and the fixes:\n\n---\n\n### 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct`\n\n**Break:** C# 13 prohibits `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` types (the compiler-synthesized `Equals`/`GetHashCode` don't account for inline array semantics).\n\n**Fix:** Use a plain `struct`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `Generator.cs` — `stackalloc` in local function inside iterator\n\n**Break:** C# 13 relaxed `unsafe` restrictions in iterators/async methods, but as a consequence, local functions inside iterators are now treated as part of the iterator state machine. `stackalloc` is still forbidden in iterators (stack frame lifetime is undefined across `yield`), so the local function's `stackalloc` now errors.\n\n**Fix:** Extract the local function to a separate `static` method:\n\n```csharp\nunsafe class DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();\n    }\n\n    static void Process()\n    {\n        int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        // ... work with pointer\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `Resolver.cs` — Overload ambiguity with `[]`\n\n**Break:** C# 13's \"first-class span types\" feature adds new implicit conversions for `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. The empty collection expression `[]` now converts equally well to both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, making the call ambiguous.\n\n**Fix:** Disambiguate with an explicit type:\n\n```csharp\nstatic void Main()\n{\n    Process(ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty);\n    // or: Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0072a92a-85d4-4edd-9476-7109fe48df9d","outputTokens":491,"requestId":"C426:2100D9:1C8B0D9:200D49E:6A07BF9B"},"id":"d21b7439-976c-40d2-8d29-f4e3cface0e1","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:48.809Z","parentId":"34c8706d-3c57-4a76-b410-395ca374f977"}
